  "text": "The Android View rendering pipeline flows through a precisely coordinated sequence of components. At the top level, Choreographer (core/java/android/view/Choreographer.java) drives the entire process through VSYNC-synchronization via its doFrame() and scheduleFrameLocked() methods. This ensures rendering is synchronized with the display refresh rate. \n\nViewRootImpl (core/java/android/view/ViewRootImpl.java) acts as the critical intermediary between the Window Manager and the view hierarchy. When setView() is called to attach a view tree to a window, ViewRootImpl orchestrates the measure-layout-draw traversal by invoking performTraversals(), which is called in response to Choreographer's frame scheduling.\n\nThe heart of the rendering pipeline is the View class (core/java/android/view/View.java). The three fundamental methods are: measure(int widthMeasureSpec, int heightMeasureSpec) which calculates the view's dimensions based on parent constraints; layout(int l, int t, int r, int b) which positions the view and its children within the parent; and draw(Canvas canvas) which renders the view's content to a canvas.\n\nFor hardware-accelerated rendering, ThreadedRenderer (core/java/android/view/ThreadedRenderer.java) extends HardwareRenderer to provide GPU-based rendering on a separate thread. It intercepts the draw() calls and redirects them to hardware acceleration.\n\nRecordingCanvas (graphics/java/android/graphics/RecordingCanvas.java) is a specialized Canvas implementation that records draw operations into display lists for deferred rendering. Rather than immediately executing drawing commands, it records them for later GPU-side execution, enabling hardware-accelerated rendering with operations recorded for efficient replay.\n\nThe complete flow is: Choreographer.doFrame() → ViewRootImpl.performTraversals() → View.measure() → View.layout() → View.draw(RecordingCanvas) → ThreadedRenderer.draw(). This pipeline ensures frames are rendered at the display's refresh rate with proper measurement and layout calculations, leveraging hardware acceleration through recorded draw operations."
}

